00:00:04.180 --> 00:00:07.910
&gt;&gt; Harrison Smith: It is
my great pleasure today

00:00:07.910 --> 00:00:12.130
to introduce Aaron Becker the
writer of a wonderful series

00:00:12.130 --> 00:00:17.520
of wordless picture books that
began in 2013 with "Journey."

00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:19.780
Not only was it the
first book in a series,

00:00:19.780 --> 00:00:25.940
it was also Aaron's first book and
earned a Caldecott honor in 2014.

00:00:25.940 --> 00:00:28.510
The New York Times critic
Sarah Harrison Smith --

00:00:28.510 --> 00:00:32.640
the other Harrison Smith -- called
it a masterwork in her review.

00:00:32.640 --> 00:00:35.210
Not a bad debut.

00:00:35.210 --> 00:00:38.810
The book tells a story of a lonely
girl with a magical red marker.

00:00:38.810 --> 00:00:42.130
She draws her way from
a drab sad-looking city

00:00:42.130 --> 00:00:45.060
to a brightly colored world
of castles and warriors

00:00:45.060 --> 00:00:47.530
and a friendly purple bird.

00:00:47.530 --> 00:00:51.570
At the flick of her marker, she can
draw a portal, a boat, a balloon,

00:00:51.570 --> 00:00:54.590
a flying carpet, and bring
all these things into life.

00:00:54.590 --> 00:00:58.160
The series continued with "Quest,"
which Kirkus Reviews described

00:00:58.160 --> 00:01:00.520 position:56%
as a wordless testament to the power

00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:03.460
of not just imagination
but art itself.

00:01:03.460 --> 00:01:06.730
